The Winchester Model 1200 is a 20-inch, 12-gauge, manually operated, slide action shotgun. The slide action, also known as a pump-action, means that the shotgun has a moving bolt system which is operated by a "wooden or composite slide called the fore-end". The fore-end is located on the underside of the barrel and moves front to back. The weapon can hold a maximum of five rounds total with four in the tubular magazine and one in the chamber. It has a hammerless action which means that there is no external hammer spur. There is only a firing pin which strikes the primer on the shell to ignite the powder in the round. title: For Sale:  Leupold Mark 4 LR/T
postcontent:
This 3.5-10x40 is the optic that the military uses on many of the MK12 Special Purpose Rifles (SPR). It is also the same optic that Marcus Luttrell was using during the 'Lone Survivor' event where he and a few other brave SEALs fought hundreds of Afghan assholes. 

The scope is in excellent condition with only the edges of the turrets shined a bit (barely noticeable) due to living and traveling in a soft case. It features an illuminated Tactical Milling Reticle that can be used as a ballistic reticle. It has been converted to .5 MOA adjustments from the Leupold custom shop and has a custom BDC turret that is calibrated to a 77 grain bullet at 2850 feet per second (determine the range and turn the elevation turret to the corresponding number). I have tested the BDC turret extensively and it is true to 600 yards which was the longest shot I could take until I recently secured a place with just over 1000 meters. Additionally, I have turrets for 62 grain 5.56, 168 grain 7.62, and the standard MOA turret.

The mount is a LaRue QD SPR mount that is also in very good condition. I have also tested the return to zero quality of this mount extensively and have never experienced a discernable shift even at 600 yards. LaRue claims that it will return to 1/10 of a MOA and after owning several of these mounts I know for a fact it is that good or better.

I am now shooting larger cartridges at greater distances and need more magnification. I'm going to have to sacrifice this Leupold to fund the high end optic for this application. After the work from the custom shop I have over $1700 in this optic and mount. I am open to offers but lowball offers will not get a response, don't waste your time. This is a face to face sale only in the North Alabama area, I will not ship. For the most part I'm interested in cash, however, I may consider a trade for ARs, AR uppers, or high end optics if something is offered that would compel me to sell something else.

title: For Sale:  1945 VK-98/  Volkssturmkarabiner or volksgewhr (peoples carbine or people rifle)
postcontent:
This is an antique with a very significant history. 
Desperation; 8mm VK-98 Volksgewehr (Top Picture)In 1945, the last year of World War II, German ordinance began production of these pieces of crap.  With the Russians approaching from the east and the Yanks and Brits closing in from the west, the Germans began mass production of the Volksgewehr (people’s rifle) in a desperate attempt to defend the motherland.  The Volksgewehr was a simple bolt action rifle manufactered to be extremely cheap and easy to produce.  Unlike the venerable 98k Mauser, this rifle was stripped down to its most basic functional parts.  It had cheap, crude sights that could not be adjusted, notice how the front sight is roughly soldered to the muzzle.  The barrel was quickly and crudely machined, notice the visible tool marks.  The stock was left unfinished and often lacked butt plates.  It also lacked an internal magazine, being single shot only.  Due to Allied bombing many of the rifles were produced by cottage industry—In small shops, garages, even people’s homes and back yards.  The purpose of this gun was to arm the newly formed Volksturm (People’s Militia), recruited mostly from old men and children.  It was hoped that by mass producing these cheap rifles the Nazi’s could arm and mobilize the entire populace of Germany, and drive back the Allies through sheer numbers.Some models did have a box magazine, called the VG-1, but lacked a knob on the bolt. Very few were produced and they are extremely rare. (Bottom Picture)Also rare, VK-98 Models chambered in 7.92 Kurz, the shortened cartridge used for the Sturmgewehr 44 assualt rifle.Today there are few surviving examples of the Volksgewehr.  Allied soldiers did not take them as war trophies and most were used for scrap metal.Value: $2,000-$4,000.Chambered in 7.92 Kurz: $4,000-$7,000.VG-1 Value: $6,000-$12,000
(This infomation I can be read off of any website with this guns history)

Action works good, fires, fully functional.  only thing id add is someone in the past added a lacquer finish.  Actually lools very nice.  And the very end of the barrel was cut off, I heard because they would not fit in a GI bag back then. Bought from a friend whose grandfather was in war.   Gun is in great shape any questions please email or call/text REDACTED
